topped hoods from offending. Drawing on a variety of sources, including interviews with perpetrators and victims of this violence, the book argues that the hoods' risky offending may amount to a game in which hoods gain prestige by displaying hard-to-fake signals of toughness to each other. Violent physical punishment feeds into this signaling game, increasing the hoods' status by proving that they have committed serious offenses and can "manfully" take punishment yet remained undeterred. A rare combination of frontline research and pioneering ideas, The Hoods has important implications for our fundamental understanding of crime and punishment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCrimevNorthern IrelandvBelfast. 0aCrimezNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aCriminalsvNorthern IrelandvBelfast. 0aCriminalszNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aJuvenile delinquentsvNorthern IrelandvBelfast. 0aJuvenile delinquentszNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aParamilitary forcesvNorthern IrelandvBelfast. 0aParamilitary forceszNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aPunishmentvNorthern IrelandvBelfast. 0aPunishmentzNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvCriminology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aBelfast.  aCatholic paramilitaries.  aCatholics.  aIRA.  aIrish Republican Army.  aLoyalist paramilitaries.  aLoyalists.  aNorthern Ireland.  aPPAs.  aProtestant paramilitaries.  aProtestants.  aRepublicans.  aadult males.  aantisocial behavior.  aantisocial behaviors.  aantisocial behaviour.  acivil conflict.  acommunity recognition.  aconflict.  acrime.  acriminal deterrence.  adelinquency.  adeterrence.  aextralegal governance.  agroup acceptance.  ahoods' subculture.  ahoods.  ajoyriding.  ajuvenile delinquency.  aoffense patterns.  aordinary crime.  apara